# SONA: Self-Optimizing Neural Architecture  How Claude Flow Routes Agents in 0.05ms

## Plain English First: What Does SONA Do?

Imagine a very experienced manager who has worked with 20 different specialists. When a new task arrives, this manager instantly knows which specialist to assign based on thousands of past decisions. They don't deliberate  the right choice just "clicks" from experience. And they get better every day.

SONA is that manager for Claude Flow. When a task arrives  a code question, an architecture decision, a debugging request  SONA decides in under 0.05 milliseconds which model, agent type, and configuration will handle it best. It learns from every decision, constantly improving its routing accuracy.

## The Core Problem SONA Solves

Claude Flow has access to many AI models and agent types:
- Claude Opus (expensive, most capable, slow)
- Claude Sonnet (balanced)
- Claude Haiku (fast, cheap, less capable)
- Specialized agents: security-architect, coder, researcher, tester, etc.

The wrong choice wastes money and time. Asking Opus to fix a one-line typo is overkill. Asking Haiku to design a distributed system architecture will produce poor results. SONA makes the right call automatically.

## How SONA Works: The Architecture

SONA combines three concepts:

### 1. Mixture of Experts (MoE)
Instead of one big neural network that handles everything, MoE has many small "expert" networks, each specializing in different task types. A "gating" network decides which experts to activate for each input.

```javascript
// Conceptual MoE structure in SONA
class MixtureOfExperts {
  constructor(numExperts = 8, topK = 2) {
    this.experts = [
      new ExpertNetwork('code-analysis'),
      new ExpertNetwork('architecture-design'),
      new ExpertNetwork('security-review'),
      new ExpertNetwork('debugging'),
      new ExpertNetwork('documentation'),
      new ExpertNetwork('testing'),
      new ExpertNetwork('performance'),
      new ExpertNetwork('general-reasoning')
    ];
    this.gate = new GatingNetwork(numExperts);
    this.topK = topK; // Activate top 2 experts per input
  }

  forward(taskEmbedding) {
    // Gate decides which experts to use
    const gateScores = this.gate.forward(taskEmbedding);
    const topExperts = topK(gateScores, this.topK);

    // Only activate the top-K experts (saves computation)
    const expertOutputs = topExperts.map(idx =>
      this.experts[idx].forward(taskEmbedding)
    );

    // Weighted combination
    return weightedSum(expertOutputs, gateScores);
  }
}
```

### 2. The Tiny Dancer Model Selector
SONA uses an extremely small neural network (the "tiny dancer") as its routing brain. It's tiny by design  the routing decision itself must be fast (0.05ms). The tiny dancer:
- Takes a compressed representation of the task
- Outputs a probability distribution over available models/agents
- Updates its weights after each decision (online learning)

```javascript
class TinyDancerSelector {
  constructor() {
    // Deliberately minimal: 3 layers, 64 hidden units
    // Fast enough to route in <0.05ms on CPU
    this.layers = [
      new DenseLayer(128, 64, 'relu'),  // Input: task embedding
      new DenseLayer(64, 32, 'relu'),
      new DenseLayer(32, 12, 'softmax') // Output: 12 agent/model options
    ];
    this.learningRate = 0.001;
  }

  route(taskEmbedding) {
    let x = taskEmbedding;
    for (const layer of this.layers) {
      x = layer.forward(x);
    }
    return x; // Probability per agent type
  }

  // Called after task completes  reward/penalize the routing choice
  learn(taskEmbedding, chosenAgent, outcome) {
    const reward = outcome.success ? outcome.qualityScore : -1;
    this.backprop(taskEmbedding, chosenAgent, reward);
  }
}
```

### 3. The 0.05ms Adaptation Loop
SONA continuously updates its routing weights using a simplified online gradient descent. Because the tiny dancer is so small, a weight update takes microseconds:

```javascript
class SONAAdaptationLoop {
  constructor() {
    this.selector = new TinyDancerSelector();
    this.historyBuffer = new CircularBuffer(1000); // Last 1000 decisions
    this.adaptationInterval = 10; // Adapt after every 10 decisions
  }

  async route(task) {
    const start = performance.now();

    // Embed the task description (fast, 1536-dim vector)
    const embedding = await this.embed(task.description);

    // Route: select best agent  THIS is the 0.05ms part
    const agentProbs = this.selector.route(embedding);
    const selectedAgent = argmax(agentProbs);

    const elapsed = performance.now() - start;
    // elapsed is typically 0.03-0.07ms

    return {
      agent: selectedAgent,
      confidence: agentProbs[selectedAgent],
      routingLatency: elapsed
    };
  }

  // Called asynchronously  doesn't block the route decision
  async recordOutcome(routingDecision, taskResult) {
    this.historyBuffer.push({ routingDecision, taskResult });

    if (this.historyBuffer.size % this.adaptationInterval === 0) {
      // Mini-batch adaptation  updates in <0.05ms
      await this.selector.learn(
        routingDecision.embedding,
        routingDecision.agent,
        taskResult
      );
    }
  }
}
```

## Using SONA via Claude Flow CLI

```bash
# Route a task through SONA's intelligence system
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest hooks route \
  --task "Design a PostgreSQL schema for multi-tenant SaaS"

# Output:
# SONA routing decision:
#   Selected: system-architect (confidence: 0.89)
#   Reasoning: architecture + database design signals
#   Model: claude-opus-4-6 (complexity score: 8.2/10)
#   Routing latency: 0.043ms

# Get an explanation of why SONA chose what it chose
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest hooks explain \
  --topic "why architect for database design"

# View SONA's current performance metrics
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest hooks metrics --v3-dashboard

# Retrain SONA on your project's patterns
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest hooks pretrain --model-type moe --epochs 10
```

## Integration with the Swarm

When you initialize a swarm, SONA is called for each task assignment:

```bash
# SONA automatically selects agents when you orchestrate
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest swarm init \
  --topology hierarchical \
  --max-agents 8 \
  --strategy specialized

# Each task gets routed through SONA:
# Task: "Fix authentication bug" -> SONA -> coder + security-auditor
# Task: "Benchmark API performance" -> SONA -> performance-engineer + tester
# Task: "Write API docs" -> SONA -> api-docs agent
```

## What Improves Over Time

SONA learns your specific project's patterns:
- If you always need the security-architect for auth changes -> SONA learns to route auth tasks there faster
- If Haiku consistently fails on architecture questions -> SONA learns to always use Opus for those
- If certain agent combinations produce better outcomes -> SONA learns to co-select them

## The Plain English Takeaway

SONA is why Claude Flow gets smarter the more you use it. Every task you run teaches it something. After a week of heavy use on Stuart's project, SONA will route tasks more accurately than it did on day one  automatically, without any configuration changes. The 0.05ms speed means routing overhead is effectively invisible.

