# ReasoningBank: How Claude Flow Learns From Every Decision It Makes

## Plain English First: The Core Idea

Every time you ask a doctor for advice, a good doctor mentally files away what worked and what didn't. Over years, they build a mental library of "if patient has symptoms X+Y+Z, treatment A worked 87% of the time."

ReasoningBank is Claude Flow's equivalent. Every task it completes  every bug fix, every architecture decision, every agent routing choice  gets stored as a "trajectory" (the full story of what happened). Next time a similar situation arises, ReasoningBank retrieves relevant past trajectories and uses them to make better decisions.

## The 4-Step Intelligence Pipeline

### Step 1: RETRIEVE  Find Relevant Past Experience

When a new task arrives, ReasoningBank searches past trajectories for similar situations using HNSW vector search:

```javascript
class ReasoningBank {
  async retrieve(currentTask) {
    // Embed the task description
    const taskEmbedding = await this.embed(currentTask.description);

    // HNSW search: find the 10 most similar past trajectories
    const similarTrajectories = await this.vectorDB.search({
      vector: taskEmbedding,
      topK: 10,
      filter: {
        // Only retrieve trajectories with positive verdicts
        minConfidence: 0.6
      }
    });

    return similarTrajectories;
  }
}
```

```bash
# Manual retrieval via CLI
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest memory search \
  --query "fix authentication JWT expiry bug" \
  --namespace patterns \
  --limit 10
```

### Step 2: JUDGE  Evaluate Past Decisions

Not all past trajectories are equally good. The JUDGE component assigns "verdicts"  was this a success? How confident?

```javascript
class TrajectoryJudge {
  async judge(trajectory) {
    const factors = {
      // Did the task complete without errors?
      taskSuccess: trajectory.outcome.errors === 0 ? 1.0 : -1.0,

      // How long did it take? (normalized against baseline)
      timeEfficiency: baseline / trajectory.duration,

      // Did tests pass?
      testCoverage: trajectory.testResults?.passRate ?? 0.5,

      // Did the user accept the output? (implicit positive signal)
      userAcceptance: trajectory.outcome.accepted ? 1.0 : 0.0,

      // Was security review clean?
      securityScore: trajectory.securityAudit?.score ?? 0.8
    };

    const confidence = weightedAverage(factors, {
      taskSuccess: 0.40,
      timeEfficiency: 0.15,
      testCoverage: 0.20,
      userAcceptance: 0.20,
      securityScore: 0.05
    });

    return {
      verdict: confidence > 0.6 ? 'success' : 'failure',
      confidence,
      factors
    };
  }
}
```

The verdict system creates a feedback loop: successful approaches get reinforced, failed approaches get down-weighted in future retrievals.

### Step 3: DISTILL  Extract What Matters

Raw trajectories are verbose  they contain the full context, every intermediate step, all the tool calls. DISTILL extracts the essential pattern using Micro-LoRA (see separate entry):

```javascript
class PatternDistiller {
  async distill(trajectories) {
    // Extract the essential pattern from successful trajectories
    const patterns = [];

    for (const traj of trajectories.filter(t => t.verdict === 'success')) {
      const pattern = {
        // What type of task was this?
        taskSignature: await this.extractSignature(traj.task),

        // What was the key decision that made it work?
        keyDecision: await this.extractKeyDecision(traj.steps),

        // What agent/model combination worked?
        routingChoice: traj.agentSelection,

        // What approach/algorithm was used?
        approach: traj.implementationPattern,

        // Distilled as a compact vector (via LoRA adapter)
        patternVector: await this.loraEncode(traj)
      };

      patterns.push(pattern);
    }

    return patterns;
  }
}
```

```bash
# Store a distilled pattern after successful work
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest memory store \
  --key "pattern-jwt-refresh-fix" \
  --value "JWT expiry: always refresh 60s before expiry, store refresh token in httpOnly cookie, never in localStorage" \
  --namespace patterns \
  --tags "auth,jwt,security"

# Train neural patterns on the approach
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest hooks post-edit \
  --file "src/auth/jwt-handler.js" \
  --train-neural true
```

### Step 4: CONSOLIDATE  Prevent Forgetting

This is where EWC++ (Elastic Weight Consolidation) comes in (see separate entry). After distilling new patterns, CONSOLIDATE integrates them without overwriting old knowledge:

```javascript
class KnowledgeConsolidator {
  async consolidate(newPatterns, existingModel) {
    // Identify which existing weights are most important
    // (using Fisher Information Matrix from EWC++)
    const importantWeights = await this.ewc.identifyImportant(existingModel);

    // Integrate new patterns while protecting important weights
    const updatedModel = await this.ewc.constrainedUpdate({
      model: existingModel,
      newPatterns,
      protectedWeights: importantWeights,
      consolidationStrength: 0.4 // How much to protect old knowledge
    });

    return updatedModel;
  }
}
```

```bash
# Trigger consolidation after a major feature completion
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest hooks worker dispatch --trigger consolidate

# Record task completion with metrics (triggers auto-consolidation)
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest hooks post-task \
  --task-id "feature-auth-v2" \
  --success true \
  --store-results true
```

## The Complete Trajectory Record

Here's what a trajectory looks like in storage:

```javascript
// Example trajectory stored in ReasoningBank
const trajectory = {
  id: 'traj-20260221-001',
  task: {
    description: 'Fix JWT token expiry causing user logouts',
    type: 'bug-fix',
    complexity: 6.2
  },
  embedding: Float32Array([...]), // HNSW-indexed vector
  steps: [
    { step: 1, action: 'search_codebase', result: 'found auth/jwt.js' },
    { step: 2, action: 'read_file', result: 'identified expiry check on line 47' },
    { step: 3, action: 'apply_fix', result: 'changed from 3600 to 3540 (refresh 60s early)' },
    { step: 4, action: 'run_tests', result: '100% pass rate' }
  ],
  agentSelection: 'coder',  // SONA's routing choice
  duration: 8420,           // ms
  outcome: { errors: 0, accepted: true },
  verdict: { verdict: 'success', confidence: 0.94 },
  distilledPattern: 'jwt-expiry-proactive-refresh',
  timestamp: '2026-02-21T10:30:00Z'
};
```

## Practical Usage: Making Claude Flow Smarter

```bash
# Before starting work: retrieve relevant past patterns
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest memory search \
  --query "authentication security patterns" \
  --namespace patterns

# After completing work: store what worked
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest memory store \
  --key "auth-pattern-$(date +%Y%m%d)" \
  --value "What worked: [description of approach]" \
  --namespace patterns

# Trigger deep learning on recent work
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest hooks worker dispatch --trigger ultralearn
```

## Why This Matters for Stuart's Projects

ReasoningBank is why Claude Flow's value compounds over time. The first week, it makes reasonably good routing decisions. After a month of active use on Ask-Ruvnet:
- It knows which bug types need security review
- It knows Stuart prefers certain code patterns
- It knows which KB operations succeed vs. fail
- It routes similar tasks instantly based on cached knowledge

The system gets smarter without you doing anything extra  just use it, and it learns.

