# Louvain Community Detection: Finding Natural Groups in Your Code and Data

## Plain English First: What Is Community Detection?

Imagine looking at a city's phone call records from above. You'd notice clusters: people in neighborhoods call each other a lot, and call outside their neighborhood less. Those natural clusters are communities. You didn't define them in advance  they emerge from the connection patterns.

Louvain Community Detection does this for any network (graph). For code: it finds which functions/modules naturally belong together based on how they call each other. For agents: it finds which agents form natural teams. For knowledge: it finds which KB entries cluster by topic.

## How Louvain Works: Greedy Modularity Optimization

Louvain optimizes "modularity"  a score that measures how much more connected nodes are within communities vs. what you'd expect by random chance.

**Modularity formula (plain English)**: For each pair of nodes in the same community, compare the actual connections to random-chance connections. If there are way more actual connections than chance, modularity is high. High modularity = good community structure.

The algorithm runs in two phases, repeated until no improvement:

**Phase 1  Local Optimization** (greedy node moves):
```javascript
// From @claude-flow/cli/dist/src/neural/graph-algorithms.js
function louvainPhase1(graph) {
  // Start: each node is its own community
  let communities = new Map(graph.nodes.map(n => [n, n]));
  let improved = true;

  while (improved) {
    improved = false;

    for (const node of graph.nodes) {
      const currentCommunity = communities.get(node);

      // Try moving this node to each neighbor's community
      let bestGain = 0;
      let bestCommunity = currentCommunity;

      for (const neighbor of graph.neighbors(node)) {
        const neighborCommunity = communities.get(neighbor);
        if (neighborCommunity === currentCommunity) continue;

        // Calculate modularity gain from this move
        const gain = modularityGain(graph, node, neighborCommunity, communities);

        if (gain > bestGain) {
          bestGain = gain;
          bestCommunity = neighborCommunity;
        }
      }

      // Move node if there's improvement
      if (bestCommunity !== currentCommunity) {
        communities.set(node, bestCommunity);
        improved = true;
      }
    }
  }

  return communities;
}
```

**Phase 2  Aggregation** (compress communities into super-nodes):
```javascript
function louvainPhase2(graph, communities) {
  // Create a new graph where each community becomes one super-node
  const superGraph = new Graph();

  // One super-node per community
  const uniqueCommunities = new Set(communities.values());
  for (const comm of uniqueCommunities) {
    superGraph.addNode(comm);
  }

  // Edges between super-nodes = sum of edges between their members
  for (const edge of graph.edges) {
    const sourceComm = communities.get(edge.source);
    const targetComm = communities.get(edge.target);
    if (sourceComm !== targetComm) {
      superGraph.addOrUpdateEdge(sourceComm, targetComm, edge.weight);
    }
  }

  return superGraph; // Repeat Phase 1 on this smaller graph
}

// Full Louvain: repeat until no improvement
function louvain(graph) {
  let currentGraph = graph;
  let allCommunities = initializeCommunities(graph);

  while (true) {
    const communities = louvainPhase1(currentGraph);
    if (!anyImprovement(communities)) break;

    allCommunities = mergeCommunities(allCommunities, communities);
    currentGraph = louvainPhase2(currentGraph, communities);
  }

  return allCommunities;
}
```

## Using Louvain via Claude Flow CLI

```bash
# Analyze your codebase to find natural module boundaries
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest hooks worker dispatch --trigger map

# This runs Louvain on the call graph of your code
# Output: groups of files/functions that naturally belong together

# Deep analysis with community detection
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest hooks worker dispatch --trigger deepdive

# For security analysis: find isolated communities
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest security scan --depth full
# Security scan uses Louvain to find components that are
# isolated from the rest (potential security concerns)
```

## Code Organization Application

```javascript
// Practical example: reorganize a large codebase
const { louvain } = await import('@claude-flow/cli/dist/src/neural/graph-algorithms.js');

// Build call graph from your code
const callGraph = await buildCallGraph('./src');
/*
  Nodes: each function/class
  Edges: function A calls function B
  Weights: call frequency
*/

// Run Louvain
const communities = louvain(callGraph);

// Result: natural module groupings
console.log(communities);
// Output:
// Community 0: [auth.js, jwt.js, session.js, middleware/auth.js]
// Community 1: [api/users.js, api/profiles.js, api/settings.js]
// Community 2: [db/queries.js, db/migrations.js, db/connection.js]
// Community 3: [utils/logger.js, utils/errors.js, utils/validators.js]

// These communities suggest your natural module boundaries!
// If auth.js and jwt.js keep calling each other but rarely
// call db/queries.js, Louvain puts them in the same community.
```

## Louvain vs. Min-Cut: When to Use Which

These algorithms are complementary, not competing:

| Question | Algorithm | Why |
|----------|-----------|-----|
| "Where are the bottlenecks/boundaries?" | Min-Cut | Finds minimum edges to split the graph |
| "What are the natural groupings?" | Louvain | Finds high-density clusters organically |
| "How many groups exist?" | Louvain | Discovers k automatically |
| "Split into exactly 2 parts at weakest point" | Min-Cut | Partition optimization |
| "Find isolated silos" | Louvain | High modularity = isolated communities |

In practice, run both:
1. Min-Cut shows WHERE the code is loosely coupled (split points)
2. Louvain shows WHAT naturally clusters together (module boundaries)

## Agent Team Formation

Claude Flow uses Louvain to form optimal agent teams:

```javascript
// Build a task dependency graph
const taskGraph = {
  nodes: ['auth-design', 'auth-impl', 'auth-test', 'api-design', 'api-impl', 'db-schema'],
  edges: [
    { source: 'auth-design', target: 'auth-impl', weight: 0.9 },
    { source: 'auth-impl', target: 'auth-test', weight: 0.8 },
    { source: 'api-design', target: 'auth-design', weight: 0.7 },
    { source: 'api-impl', target: 'db-schema', weight: 0.85 }
  ]
};

const teams = louvain(taskGraph);
// Team A: [auth-design, auth-impl, auth-test] -> Assign: security-architect + coder + tester
// Team B: [api-design, api-impl, db-schema] -> Assign: system-architect + backend-dev
```

## Performance Characteristics

- **Time complexity**: O(n log n)  nearly linear, very fast
- **Quality**: Near-optimal modularity in practice
- **Scale**: Handles graphs with millions of nodes
- **Deterministic?**: No  different runs may find different (equally good) communities

## The Plain English Takeaway

Louvain is how Claude Flow "sees" the structure of your codebase and knowledge base without you having to define it. It discovers the natural organization that already exists in the connection patterns. Use it when you want to understand what belongs together  for refactoring, for agent team formation, or for organizing knowledge.

