# Spectral Clustering: When You Need Precise K-Cluster Grouping

## Plain English First: What Makes Spectral Clustering Different?

Louvain community detection discovers how many groups exist naturally. Spectral clustering is for when you KNOW how many groups you want (k) and need mathematically precise boundaries.

Another difference: spectral clustering can find groups with non-convex shapes  like a ring, a spiral, or two interleaved crescents. Standard k-means can only find roughly spherical clusters. Spectral clustering works on the graph structure, not the raw coordinates, so shape doesn't matter.

Think of it like this: you have a jigsaw puzzle and you want exactly 5 sections. Louvain finds the natural section boundaries. Spectral clustering cuts it into exactly 5 pieces at the mathematically optimal seams.

## The Three-Step Process

### Step 1: Graph Laplacian (Capturing Connectivity)

The Laplacian matrix encodes the graph's connectivity structure:

```javascript
// From @claude-flow/cli/dist/src/neural/graph-algorithms.js
function computeLaplacian(adjacencyMatrix) {
  const n = adjacencyMatrix.length;
  const degreeMatrix = new Array(n).fill(0).map(() => new Array(n).fill(0));
  const laplacian = new Array(n).fill(0).map(() => new Array(n).fill(0));

  // Degree matrix: diagonal with sum of each row
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    const degree = adjacencyMatrix[i].reduce((sum, w) => sum + w, 0);
    degreeMatrix[i][i] = degree;
  }

  // Laplacian = Degree - Adjacency
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    for (let j = 0; j < n; j++) {
      laplacian[i][j] = degreeMatrix[i][j] - adjacencyMatrix[i][j];
    }
  }

  // Normalized Laplacian (better for graphs with varying node degrees)
  return normalizedLaplacian(laplacian, degreeMatrix);
}
```

**Why the Laplacian?** Its eigenvectors capture the graph's "vibration modes"  the natural ways the graph can be split. The k smallest eigenvectors correspond to the k best split directions.

### Step 2: Power Iteration (Finding Eigenvectors Efficiently)

Computing eigenvectors exactly is expensive. Claude Flow uses power iteration  a fast approximation:

```javascript
function powerIteration(matrix, numEigenvectors, iterations = 100) {
  const n = matrix.length;
  // Start with random vectors
  let eigenvectors = Array.from({ length: numEigenvectors }, () =>
    new Float32Array(n).map(() => Math.random())
  );

  for (let iter = 0; iter < iterations; iter++) {
    // Multiply matrix by each eigenvector
    eigenvectors = eigenvectors.map(v => matmul(matrix, v));

    // Orthogonalize (Gram-Schmidt): ensure vectors point different directions
    eigenvectors = gramSchmidt(eigenvectors);

    // Normalize
    eigenvectors = eigenvectors.map(v => normalize(v));
  }

  return eigenvectors; // k eigenvectors, each of length n
}
```

### Step 3: K-Means on Eigenvector Representation

Now each node is represented as a point in k-dimensional space (using the k eigenvectors as coordinates). Standard k-means finds k clusters:

```javascript
function spectralClustering(graph, k) {
  // Build adjacency matrix
  const adjacency = buildAdjacencyMatrix(graph);

  // Compute graph Laplacian
  const laplacian = computeLaplacian(adjacency);

  // Find k eigenvectors via power iteration
  const eigenvectors = powerIteration(laplacian, k);

  // Embed each node in k-dimensional space
  // Node i's coordinates = [eigenvector1[i], eigenvector2[i], ..., eigenvectorK[i]]
  const nodeEmbeddings = graph.nodes.map((node, i) =>
    eigenvectors.map(ev => ev[i])
  );

  // Run k-means on these embeddings
  const clusters = kMeans(nodeEmbeddings, k);

  // Map cluster assignments back to original nodes
  return new Map(graph.nodes.map((node, i) => [node, clusters[i]]));
}
```

## Spectral vs. Louvain: The Decision Guide

| Situation | Use Spectral | Use Louvain |
|-----------|-------------|-------------|
| You know exactly how many groups you need | Yes | No |
| You want to discover the natural number of groups | No | Yes |
| Groups may have irregular shapes | Yes | Either |
| Performance on very large graphs (1M+ nodes) | No (slower) | Yes |
| You need reproducible results | Yes (deterministic) | No (stochastic) |
| Clustering knowledge base topics | Either | Louvain easier |
| Splitting agents into exactly N teams | Yes | No |

## Applications in Claude Flow

### KB Topic Clustering
```javascript
// Cluster your knowledge base into exactly 10 topic areas
const kbEntries = await db.query(
  'SELECT id, embedding FROM openclaw_memory.operational_knowledge'
);

// Build similarity graph from embeddings
const similarityGraph = buildCosineSimilarityGraph(kbEntries, threshold = 0.7);

// Cluster into exactly 10 topics
const topicClusters = spectralClustering(similarityGraph, k = 10);
// Cluster 0: auth, jwt, session (15 entries)
// Cluster 1: vector search, HNSW, embeddings (22 entries)
// ... etc
```

### Agent Specialization
```javascript
// Divide 50 task types into exactly 8 agent specializations
const taskTypeGraph = buildTaskSimilarityGraph(historicalTasks);
const agentSpecializations = spectralClustering(taskTypeGraph, k = 8);

// Each specialization maps to one agent type:
// Specialization 0: security tasks -> security-architect
// Specialization 1: UI tasks -> frontend-dev
// ... etc
```

### Using via Claude Flow
```bash
# Claude Flow uses spectral clustering internally for:
# 1. Agent pool specialization (divides tasks into exactly N agent types)
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest swarm init \
  --topology hierarchical \
  --max-agents 8 \
  --strategy specialized  # <-- triggers spectral clustering for specialization

# 2. KB organization (after large ingestion, clusters into topics)
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest hooks worker dispatch --trigger map

# 3. Neural pattern organization
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest neural patterns --list
```

## Performance Characteristics

```
Time complexity: O(n^3) for exact eigenvectors, O(n * k * iterations) with power iteration
Space: O(n^2) for adjacency matrix
Quality: Mathematically optimal for graph partitioning
Deterministic: Yes (given same random seed)
Good for: < 100,000 nodes with known k
```

## The Plain English Takeaway

Spectral clustering is the precision instrument. When you know exactly how many groups you want and need guaranteed optimal boundaries, spectral clustering delivers. It's slower than Louvain and requires knowing k upfront  but it finds group structures that other algorithms miss. In Claude Flow, it's used behind the scenes when agent team sizes are fixed or when the KB needs to be organized into exactly N topic areas.

