# Bridge and Articulation Point Detection: Finding Critical Single Points of Failure

## Plain English First: What Are Bridges and Articulation Points?

**Bridge**: An edge (connection) in a network whose removal splits the network into disconnected pieces. Like a literal bridge  if it collapses, two towns lose contact with each other.

**Articulation Point**: A node (component) in a network whose removal splits the network into disconnected pieces. Like a key person in an organization  if they leave, two teams lose their connection.

In software systems:
- **Bridge**: A function or module that's the ONLY connection between two subsystems
- **Articulation Point**: A service or component that's the ONLY thing keeping two parts of your system connected

Finding these is critical for resilience planning: "What breaks everything if it breaks?"

## The Algorithm: DFS with Discovery Times

The classic algorithm uses Depth-First Search (DFS) and tracks two values per node:
- `disc[v]`: When was node v first discovered?
- `low[v]`: What's the earliest discovery time reachable from v's subtree?

If `low[neighbor] > disc[v]`, then the edge (v, neighbor) is a bridge  the neighbor's subtree can't reach anything discovered before v, so removing this edge disconnects the neighbor's subtree.

```javascript
// From @claude-flow/cli/dist/src/neural/graph-algorithms.js
class BridgeDetector {
  constructor(graph) {
    this.graph = graph;
    this.disc = new Map();    // Discovery time
    this.low = new Map();     // Lowest reachable discovery time
    this.visited = new Set();
    this.bridges = [];        // Found bridges
    this.articulationPts = new Set(); // Found articulation points
    this.timer = 0;
  }

  findBridges() {
    // Run DFS from each unvisited node (handles disconnected graphs)
    for (const node of this.graph.nodes) {
      if (!this.visited.has(node)) {
        this.dfsForBridges(node, null);
      }
    }
    return this.bridges;
  }

  dfsForBridges(node, parent) {
    this.visited.add(node);
    this.disc.set(node, this.timer);
    this.low.set(node, this.timer);
    this.timer++;

    let childCount = 0; // For articulation point detection at root

    for (const neighbor of this.graph.neighbors(node)) {
      if (neighbor === parent) continue; // Skip back edge to parent

      if (!this.visited.has(neighbor)) {
        // Tree edge: recurse
        childCount++;
        this.dfsForBridges(neighbor, node);

        // Update low value: can we reach something earlier via neighbor?
        this.low.set(node,
          Math.min(this.low.get(node), this.low.get(neighbor))
        );

        // BRIDGE CHECK: neighbor can't reach above node -> bridge!
        if (this.low.get(neighbor) > this.disc.get(node)) {
          this.bridges.push({ from: node, to: neighbor });
        }

        // ARTICULATION POINT CHECK:
        // Non-root: if low[neighbor] >= disc[node], node is AP
        if (parent !== null && this.low.get(neighbor) >= this.disc.get(node)) {
          this.articulationPts.add(node);
        }

      } else {
        // Back edge: update low with already-visited neighbor
        this.low.set(node,
          Math.min(this.low.get(node), this.disc.get(neighbor))
        );
      }
    }

    // Root is AP if it has more than one child in DFS tree
    if (parent === null && childCount > 1) {
      this.articulationPts.add(node);
    }
  }

  findArticulationPoints() {
    this.findBridges(); // Runs combined DFS
    return Array.from(this.articulationPts);
  }
}

// Usage
const detector = new BridgeDetector(codebaseGraph);
const bridges = detector.findBridges();
const criticalComponents = detector.findArticulationPoints();
```

## Practical Application: Codebase Resilience Analysis

```javascript
// Build call graph of your codebase
const callGraph = await buildCallGraph('./src');

const detector = new BridgeDetector(callGraph);
const bridges = detector.findBridges();
const articulationPoints = detector.findArticulationPoints();

console.log('=== CRITICAL DEPENDENCIES ===');
console.log('\nBridges (single connections between subsystems):');
bridges.forEach(b => {
  console.log(`  ${b.from} -> ${b.to}`);
  console.log(`   If this connection breaks, these subsystems disconnect`);
});

console.log('\nArticulation Points (critical single components):');
articulationPoints.forEach(ap => {
  console.log(`  ${ap}`);
  console.log(`   If this fails, your system splits into isolated parts`);
});

// Example output:
// Bridges:
//   auth/jwt.js -> api/middleware.js
//    If this connection breaks, API has no auth check
//
// Articulation Points:
//   db/connection.js
//    If this fails, your system splits into isolated parts
//   (both auth and api depend on it as their only DB access point)
```

## Relationship to Min-Cut: How They Complement Each Other

Min-Cut and Bridge Detection are related but different:

| Feature | Bridge Detection | Min-Cut |
|---------|-----------------|----------|
| What it finds | All edges that alone disconnect the graph | The minimum set of edges to disconnect |
| Cost/weight | Ignores weights | Finds minimum-weight cut |
| Output | ALL bridges | ONE optimal partition |
| Use case | Finding every vulnerability | Optimal partitioning |
| Relationship | Bridges ARE min-cuts of weight 1 | Generalization of bridges |

In practice, run both:
1. Bridge detection: "What are all our single points of failure?"
2. Min-cut: "If we had to split this system, where's the optimal split?"

## Claude Flow Security Integration

```bash
# Security scan uses bridge/AP detection to find vulnerabilities
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest security scan --depth full

# The scan reports:
# CRITICAL: Single points of failure detected
# - auth/session-store.js is an articulation point
#   (auth, API, and admin all route through it exclusively)
# - [admin-api -> public-api] is a bridge
#   (admin actions flow through this single connection)

# Performance analysis using bridge detection
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest performance profile --target dependency-graph
# Identifies which services are bridges (high failure impact)

# Generate resilience report
npx @claude-flow/cli@latest security audit
# Lists all bridges + articulation points with risk scores
```

## Real-World Example: Ask-Ruvnet Architecture

Running bridge detection on Ask-Ruvnet's service graph might reveal:

```
Articulation Points Found:
  1. src/core/RuvectorStore.js
     - 8 other modules connect through ONLY this file to PostgreSQL
     - Risk: If RuvectorStore fails, ALL KB operations fail
     - Mitigation: Add connection pooling + failover

  2. .mcp.json configuration
     - All MCP servers depend on this single config file
     - Risk: If config corrupts, all 96 MCP tools go offline
     - Mitigation: Auto-backup before every MCP config change

Bridges Found:
  1. PostgreSQL port 5435 -> application layer
     - Only one connection path between DB and app
     - Risk: DB restart = full outage
     - Mitigation: Connection pool with retry logic
```

## Performance Characteristics

- **Time complexity**: O(V + E)  linear in nodes and edges. Very fast.
- **Space complexity**: O(V) for discovery time and low arrays
- **Handles disconnected graphs**: Yes (outer loop handles multiple components)
- **Handles directed graphs**: Slight modification needed (check strongly connected components instead)

## The Plain English Takeaway

Bridge and articulation point detection is your "what breaks everything?" analysis tool. Before deploying, before refactoring, before making a dependency change  run this and know exactly which components are load-bearing walls in your architecture. Remove them without a plan and the whole building comes down. Claude Flow's security scanner uses this automatically, surfacing these risks before they become production incidents.

